<chapter id="using" xreflabel="Using the Python Roll">

<title>Using the Python Roll</title>

<section id="environment_modules" xreflabel="Environment Modules for Python">
	<title>Environment Modules for Python</title>

<para>
As of Rocks 6.2 (Sidewinder), Environment Modules are utilized to control
Python path names.  
</para>

<itemizedlist>

<listitem>
<para>
To see the currently loaded modules:
</para>

<screen>
% module list
Currently Loaded Modulefiles:
  1) rocks-openmpi
%
</screen>
</listitem>

<listitem>
<para>
To see available modules:
</para>

<screen>
% module avail
------------------------ /usr/share/Modules/modulefiles ------------------------
dot           module-info   null          use.own
module-cvs    modules       opt-python    rocks-openmpi

%
</screen>

</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>
To load the opt-python module:
</para>

<screen>
% module load opt-python
% module list
Currently Loaded Modulefiles:
  1) rocks-openmpi   2) opt-python
</screen>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>

</section>

<section id="using-python" xreflabel="Using the Python Roll">
<title>Using the Python Roll</title>

<para>
The Python roll installs Python versions 2.7.6 and 3.3.4.  These are
installed in <filename class="directory">/opt/python</filename>.
</para>

<para>
The Python roll installs Environment Modules files for Python 2.7.6
and 3.3.4. These are installed in <filename class="directory">/usr/share/Modules/modulefiles</filename>.
</para>

<para>
<emphasis>Numpy</emphasis> 1.8.0 is compiled and installed with Python 2.7.
</para>

<para>
Tutorials for using Python and its components are available from
the <ulink url="http://www.python.org">Python website</ulink>.  Tutorials
for using NumPy are available from
the <ulink url="http://www.numpy.org/">NumPy website</ulink>.
</para>

</section>
</chapter>
